curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com | sh
sudo systemctl enable --now docker
docker --version
2Ô∏è‚É£ Open Port 19999
For UFW Firewall:
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo ufw allow 19999/tcp
For AWS EC2:
Go to Security Group of your instance

Add Inbound Rule:

Type: Custom TCP

Port: 19999

Source: 0.0.0.0/0 (or your IP for security)

3Ô∏è‚É£ Run Netdata via Docker
bash
Copy
Edit
docker run -d --name=netdata --restart unless-stopped \
  -p 19999:19999 \
  --cap-add SYS_PTRACE \
  --security-opt apparmor=unconfined \
  -v netdata-config:/etc/netdata \
  -v netdata-lib:/var/lib/netdata \
  -v netdata-cache:/var/cache/netdata \
  -v /etc/passwd:/host/etc/passwd:ro \
  -v /etc/group:/host/etc/group:ro \
  -v /proc:/host/proc:ro \
  -v /sys:/host/sys:ro \
  -v /etc/os-release:/host/etc/os-release:ro \
  -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock \
  netdata/netdata
4Ô∏è‚É£ Access the Dashboard
On same machine: http://localhost:19999

From another device: http://<your-public-ip>:19999

5Ô∏è‚É£ Explore Metrics
System Overview ‚Üí CPU, Memory, Load, Swap

Disks ‚Üí I/O, space usage

Network ‚Üí Bandwidth usage

Containers ‚Üí Per-container CPU & RAM (Docker charts)

Alerts ‚Üí Go to Health ‚Üí All Alerts for warnings/errors

6Ô∏è‚É£ View Logs
bash
Copy
Edit
docker logs netdata | tail -n 50
docker exec -it netdata bash
ls -lah /var/log/netdata
cat /var/log/netdata/error.log | tail -n 50
exit
